Anonymous Tue 14 Sep 2021 01:54:50 No.41624409 Report
Quoted By: >>41624713 >>41625549
>>41624212
Write a less than one page short for each character that appears in Ch 1. Pack as much as you can into the fewest words (while still filling most of a page). Try to sculpt the prose for each short to fit their personality. Each short should be a mundane event in their lives prior to the story beginning, before they've met each other in all cases that apply.

This should clear up the "vague" a bit, and build back-story & personality in your head for each character. Pieces of these backstories might even make it into the story you're trying to write. Important here is to tailor the wording for each short to the personality of each character. This will help you fix dialogue that comes out of their mouths so everyone doesn't sound like you expositing about the story ... they each have their own dialect, word choices, & accent dictated by their personality and life experiences.

Anonymous Tue 14 Sep 2021 02:39:49 No.41625549 Report

>>41624713
This advice >>41624409 is good even if there is no dialogue. It's an exercise designed to flesh out the personality of any character currently the focus of the writing. Each sentence dedicated to what a character is doing, thinking, experiencing from their surrounding should be reflected somewhat in the vocabulary & grammar choices that express that character's personality & point of view.

I suggested short, mundane incidents described could be world-building for the character, but they are also world-building in general for the story. Various mechanics, history, assumptions etc. will affect that encapsulated experience.

Alternately, place the character in an entirely different world. Perhaps they're in our world, they walk into a fast food restaurant and order a meal. How are they experiencing the world & people around them while performing such a normal, every day task? Their order takes too long to be filled. How do they respond? Patiently wait, or harass the employees for an answer? The order arrives and it's wrong. Do they demand a new order? Quietly seethe & eat it anyway? Philosophically enjoy it for what it is?

It's an exercise in developing the personality of each character, getting inside their head, following their internal monologue, describing their memories & feelings as they experience this normal, everyday scene in their lives. Some characters will take elaborate, complex sentences with unusual vocabulary to fit their personality, Others take simple sentences with staccato & abrupt language.

Etc.

And, yes, that will also express via their dialogue when that happens.

If there are only two characters in Ch. 1, go ahead and pull another two or three from Ch. 2 until inspiration clarifies how events in the story actual will be told. Deliberately try to break your normal grammar patterns. Read a page of Shakespeare, and then one of Chaucer to shake your habits up a bit. Some Mark Twain & Jack London can't hurt either.
